In this study,
 we employed an inverse probability weighting approach to account for missing data,
 using empirical frequencies as our estimate for the observation probabilities under a Missing Completely at Random (MCAR) assumption.
 While this method is objective and straightforward,
 it can be susceptible to high variance if some pairwise observations are rare,
 leading to unstable weights.
 For future research,
 particularly in contexts with sparse data,
 more advanced methods for estimating these probabilities could be considered.
 One promising direction is to use an Empirical Bayes framework,
 such as a Beta-Binomial model,
 to produce stabilized "shrinkage" estimates.
 Such an approach would "borrow strength" across all pairs to improve the probability estimates for rare pairs,
 potentially leading to a more efficient and stable final estimator without sacrificing the objectivity of being entirely data-driven.
 This could offer a principled way to balance the trade-off between bias and variance in the estimation of the weights,
 enhancing the robustness of the overall findings.
